			<outline text="January 26" created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 16:45:14 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="26">
				<outline text="Revisiting Org Mode" created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 16:58:59 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="For grins, I am &lt;a href=&quot;https://orgmodeforbeginners.com/&quot;&gt;taking another look at org mode&lt;/a&gt;, which is an editing add-on to emacs. As far as I can tell the intent of org mode is to provide outline  functionality to emacs, but the  key thing to know is that emacs pre-dates graphical user interfaces, so for it to graphically depict an outline it uses asterisks. One of the keys, I think, to understanding org mode is to realize the focus of it is really on the keyboard bindings that make it easier to edit an outline without using a mouse. " created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 16:45:15 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="One can say that the above really defines emacs, those who use it proficiently and evangelize its functionality to do because they have built the  memory muscle to write, edit, move text, and navigate within files (documents) quickly via the keyboard.  " created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 16:49:54 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="But, when I look at an outline in emacs/org mode I am not sure what I think I see is in fact an outline. Outlines predate computers, and outlines written on paper with pencil are graphical; child branches (nodes) are indented beneath the parent branches and so your eyes easily see the structure, which is in fact the whole point of an outline. I don't see that structure when I look at an outline in org mode, I see a series of lines with a number preceding asterisks, which is basically a list. " created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 16:51:41 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="All this prologue to ask the question, what really is an outline and what is an outline editor? I am writing this in Drummer and I easily and quickly recognize this text is in an outline form because there is a structure of indentation that shows child and parent nodes. Drummer also clearly demonstrates the value of the mouse. In Drummer to collapse the child nodes of a parent I simply double-click the parent node, which I find intuitive. With org mode enabled, one presses the Tab key to expand and collapse. Fast yes, but is it intuitive? " created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 16:56:28 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Seems to me that the real primary benefit of using org mode is that your data is stored in a &quot;plain&quot; text file format that makes the data the most portable because one can open and easily read those files using an editor on any computing platform known to man. My files created and edited using Drummer are also in a text format but it includes markup that has the purpose of being understood by a computer more so than by a human. I can open the Drummer OPML files using an editor on any computing platform known to man but it is not going to be as legible in that editor as an org mode file is going to be.  " created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 17:02:44 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="The debate here then is on what is the most important to oneself, future proofing of the accessibility and legibility of what is written, or the lower cognitive load of using modern tools, by which I mean the computer mouse, to navigate and manipulate an outline? I think &lt;a href=&quot;https://frankmcpherson.blog/2024/01/25/i-had-not.html&quot;&gt;the computer mouse&lt;/a&gt; and outlines are natural siblings, and it seems silly to me to not use the technology that is available to me. " created="Fri, 26 Jan 2024 17:08:12 GMT" type="outline"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
