			<outline text="January 24" created="Wed, 24 Jan 2024 15:43:24 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="24">
				<outline text="Note to self: when you copy nodes from your Daynotes outline to your microBlog outline, the created date carries over and will be used as the published date when publishing to microblog. What this means is that you could go back and time and post on a date in the past if youi copy over something you wrote in the Daynotes outline yesterday. If you don't want this then change the date before you publish." created="Wed, 24 Jan 2024 21:42:37 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Now that I am annotating more PDFs using the Boox Note Air 3C I am looking for ways to make the annotations searchable as that is not what is produced by the Boox software. Today tried &lt;a href=&quot;https://getsearchablepdf.com/&quot;&gt;GetSearchablePDF&lt;/a&gt; that works fairly well, but is very expensive at $9 per 100 pages scanned. I wonder what cheaper and perhaps self-hosted solutions exist?" created="Wed, 24 Jan 2024 20:13:17 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Putting this here for me to listen to: &lt;a href=&quot;https://overcast.fm/+65w4Dhgms&quot;&gt;Rabbit CEO Jesse Jyu on This Week In Startups&lt;/a&gt; talking about the R1. " created="Wed, 24 Jan 2024 15:43:25 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 23" created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 18:58:27 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="23">
				<outline text="Reading &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.com/2014/01/24/30thAnniversaryOfMac.html&quot;&gt;Dave Winer's recollection&lt;/a&gt; of first seeing and using the Mac on the 30th anniversary of its introduction has me reflecting on my first encounters with the Mac during my freshman year of college in 1984-85. My work study assignment was the undergraduate computer science lab that was for all practical purposes put together specifically to be the home for six of the newly minted Macs. The CS department used the lab for teaching an experimental class in Pascal, but also came equipped with MacWrite and MacPaint. I was immediately enamored by these little computers that I had the good fortune to use whenever there were no other students using them, and I lusted over them for all five years I was in school. The price for the Macs were well out of my price range as were the IBM PCs that I could buy on a student discount. The first computer that I purchased was an &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.computinghistory.org.uk/det/3959/Atari-800XL/&quot;&gt;Atari 800XL&lt;/a&gt; during my sophmore year, which I used for programming classes via VT100 terminal emulation connection to a mainframe and for writing papers. After I got my first job I bought an &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.myoldcomputers.com/museum/computers/atari_1040st.htm&quot;&gt;Atari 1040ST&lt;/a&gt;, which mimics the Mac UI but cost much less. Finally I bought my first Mac, a Mac Mini in 2005. " created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 19:02:38 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I saw some re-occurrences of the RDP encryption connection errors yesterday after I made the registry change to disable UDP. Last night we had a power outage that caused the host of my remote desktop to reboot and today I am observing that I have yet to see a connection error, which makes me wonder whether there is some type of network connectivity issue with that host." created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 18:58:28 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Syncing Files With The Note Air 3C" created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 21:38:09 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I bought the Boox Note Air 3C for the ability to better hand write notes in digital ink and to read with less eye strain. Reading and writing with any mobile device means you are going to need a way to get files on and off the mobile device. Curiously, Boox treats synchronization of the native notes apps different from annotations made with the native reading app. " created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 21:39:04 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Part of the set up process is configuring the Note Air 3C to use one of several different public clouds by what Boox calls &quot;binding&quot; your public cloud account to the device. I choose OneDrive and after binding that account a new &quot;onyx&quot; folder was created in my OneDrive files that has a subfolder named &quot;NoteAir 3C&quot; and within that are two subfolders, &quot;Notepads&quot; and &quot;Reading Notes.&quot; As far as I can tell the only thing that ends up in these folders is the output of the native Notes app. " created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 21:44:18 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The &quot;Notepads&quot; folder contains PDF copies of each notepad one creates in Notes, I believe this corresponds to the sync format option I select in the Sync Settings of the Notes app. The &quot;Reading Notes&quot; contain copies of Notepads that are associated to the &quot;books&quot; (PDFs or ePub) that one is reading and created via the split view mode. It appears that once the handwritten notes notepad is first created in split view you can then open that notepad like any other and continue reading, but basically that one file is what opens when you select to open handwritten notes in split view." created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 21:50:51 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I should add that during the device set up you also create an account in what is called the Onyx Cloud that has servers in the United States and Europe. Here too, only PDF copies of your notepads are synced along with data about PDFs and ePub books you read.  As far as I can tell the reading data is basically what page you are on and what percentage of the &quot;book&quot; you have read. It looks like there is an ability to turn off syncing of notes to the Onyx account, but there is a warning about manual sync being disabled after you turn it off. It looks like you can also configure to sync the &quot;.note&quot; file that is a BOOX exclusive format, but you can only select one of the format options." created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 21:49:05 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Bottom line is that PDF copies of the notepads that I create on the Boox Note Air 3C are written to OneDrive and can also be written to the Onyx Cloud or can be configured to only be written to the cloud storage of your choice. What is not written to either of these locations are any books, PDFS or ePub, that you copy to and possibly annotate on the device. Because you can annotate PDFs, it is common to use PDFs as templates for specific formated notepad like daily planners or meeting planners, however what is important to know is what you do annotate is not automatically backed up to any of the sync locations you may have created for your Notepads." created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 22:43:38 GMT"/>
					<outline text="So far I have not found where the notepad files are actually stored in the storage of the device. The only files I can see via the Storage tab of the device are the book files (PDFs or ePub) that appear when I tap Documents from the storage tab, but what displays on the Storage tab appears to be a label for file types and most like the files you see in Documents are actually stored in the Books folder on the device." created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 22:39:54 GMT"/>
					<outline text="One can add or &quot;push&quot; book files to the Note Air using the BOOXDrop app, which is a web browser that runs on the device that you can access via a home network using the IP address provided by the app, but this doesn't provide an easy way to sync annotated books back to another device. What I have done is install SyncThing on the NoteAir and peered it with a server running in my home network. I also have SyncThing installed on my desktop computer and have configured the desktop, server, and NoteAir to share a folder. The folder I am sharing on the NoteAir 3C is the Books folder, and so whenever a file in that folder changes the changed file is synchronized to my server and also with the desktop computer. I can then open that PDF on my desktop when I want and well as easily copy/sync PDFs from my desktop to the Note Air. " created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 22:48:34 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I don't keep SyncThing continually running on the Note Air, though I could configure it do so, but that comes at a cost of battery life. I prefer to manually control synchronization by starting up and existing the app. I use SyncThing in this same way on my Pixel 7a smartphone to make a local backup copy of my photos. " created="Tue, 23 Jan 2024 22:54:49 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 22" created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 16:54:10 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="22">
				<outline text="I use Microsoft's Remote Desktop (RDP) app with Windows 11 to access and use several remote desktops in my homelab. Ever since I upgraded my work PC to Windows 11 I started frequently experiencing disconnections due to an encryption error. Like many annoying problems, this one isn't consistent, it seems to start occuring over time. I did some searching and found information suggesting a bug with RDP could be the issue with a recommended work around of disabling UDB for RDP via a registry entry, which I have done. Let's see how this goes." created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 16:54:11 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Parting Ways With Evernote" created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 19:17:05 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="Today I canceled my subscription and closed by account with &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evernote&quot;&gt;Evernote&lt;/a&gt;, which most will think a trivial event. People stop using software all the time, except I've been using Evernote from the beginning that it first became available for Windows in 2008. In fact, I am pretty sure that I first used a beta version of the product perhaps as early as 2005. At the time it was introduced no company was really developing notetaking software, at least not for Windows. When first introduced the UI of EverNote had the form of a continual scroll of information &quot;flagged&quot; by date, in fact it could be my first experience with the newsfeed/stream UI now commonly used by social networking applications. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 19:17:20 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="The closest resemblance EverNote had to any other product was &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pinterest.com/pin/newton-os-gui--369998925635580915/&quot;&gt;the UI of the Newton OS&lt;/a&gt; that ran on Apple's Newton Messagepad.  The resemblance may have been intentional because EverNote was founded by &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stepan_Pachikov&quot;&gt;Stepan Pachikov&lt;/a&gt; who with his company Paragraph International, lead the development of the handwriting recognition engine known as &lt;a href=&quot;https://apple.fandom.com/wiki/CalliGrapher&quot;&gt;CalliGrapher&lt;/a&gt;, which was licensed by Apple for use with the &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton_OS&quot;&gt;Newton OS&lt;/a&gt;. EverNote's resemblance to Newton definitely drew my attention to the product. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 19:24:23 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Pachikov brought &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Libin&quot;&gt;Phil Libin&lt;/a&gt; onboard as CEO of Evernote (originally the product name had a capitalized N that was changed to lowercase by 2008) and Libin grew the company and the product into the well recognized, multi-platform product that most people know of it today. In my opinion what made Evernote attractive is that it centrally stored data (perhaps one of the first commercial client/server applications) that is accessible to client applications running on nearly every computing platform that I use. At a time when it was common to see applications that ran only on Mac or Windows, or iOS, Evernote ran any every single one of these platforms. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 19:32:15 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Of course, developing and then maintaining separate code bases for each platform is daunting, particularly if the application architecture was not explicitly developed for that use, and so over time bugs crept up that caused problems. The relatively fast growth of the product also lead to performance issues, and for some data loss.  For me Evernote &lt;a href=&quot;https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/JumpingTheShark&quot;&gt;jumped the shark&lt;/a&gt; around 2013 when the company began licensing/selling products with Evernote branding, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.engadget.com/2016-02-02-evernote-online-market-closes.html&quot;&gt;like socks&lt;/a&gt;, that had no relationship to the core product, while there were significant problems with the Evernote app. One year after Libin left Evernote the company stopped selling these products. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 19:44:16 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="It might be said that Evernote began its path of decent soon after Libin left the company in 2015. Key developers started to leave the company and  soon there  seemed to be yearly rumors of the company going under. While many who I associated with stopped using it, by 2015 I had accumulated seven years of information in the application and I felt the yearly $60 subscription was worth my continued access to that information from all the devices I use. The Evernote web clipper had become my most valued tool of all the software I use and it is still the best browser web clipping application available particularly on mobile devices. Unlike most other apps, sharing to Evernote on iOS and Android captures the entire web page rather than just the link to the page. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 19:53:00 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="So, despite the dismal outlook for the company and the app, I stayed committed to it, but last year it was acquired by Bending Spoons and they changed &lt;a href=&quot;https://evernote.com/compare-plans&quot;&gt;the subscription cost to $15 per month&lt;/a&gt;, which I decided was too expensive in light of what I pay in other software subscriptions. When the rumors of the demise of Evernote started appearing I began testing ways to export my information out of the application and import it into others. Two years ago I exported everything from Evernote to OneNote, which wasn't perfect but good enough for me to find information should I need to. Last year I found I could also import my Evernote archive into Obsidian, which I completed last fall and from that point stopped storing new information in Evernote. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 20:00:02 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="My yearly subscription with Evernote renews at the end of January, so my deadline to delete my data from Evernote and close my account was this past weekend. Deleting my notes was much more laborious than I would have preferred, as a deleted note is moved to Trash and then one has to empty the Trash in order to completely delete the note and I found that Trash emptying seemed to only handle about 100 notes or so at a time, particularly with the web application. The problem seems to be with the synchronization performance, even the web app syncs data with the browser local storage, and I suspect there is Javasript handling all of the API calls to tell Evernote's servers to move and delete data. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 20:06:36 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="I am obviously much more brand loyal than most other people, so it's really a big deal for me personally to stop using a product after having used it for more than ten years. Obviously, my issue is not with the product itself but the subscription cost that most likely is driven by a decreasing number of subscribers. I do expect Evernote to eventually disappear within the next year or two. Going forward I am using &lt;a href=&quot;https://joplinapp.org/help/&quot;&gt;Joplin&lt;/a&gt; to capture web clippings from Mac and Linux, tolerating the fact that sharing to Joplin with iPad only captures the link and not the web content. I have also started using &lt;a href=&quot;https://archivebox.io/&quot;&gt;Archivebox&lt;/a&gt; on my home network. I am using end to end encryption with Joplin and using OneDrive as the &quot;hub&quot; for storing/syncing the data in Joplin between my desktops and iPad. Unfortunately the Android version of Joplin does not synchronize well and I gave up even trying to use it on my Pixel 7a. " created="Mon, 22 Jan 2024 20:11:55 GMT" type="outline"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 19" created="Fri, 19 Jan 2024 14:23:07 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="19">
				<outline text="Last night I tried the different refresh modes of the Boox Note Air 3C. I've been using the Balanced mode that is described as having &quot;slightly heavier ghosting, suitable for thumbing through documents&quot; but changed to HD mode that is described as having &quot;good display effect, suitable for general text reading.&quot; Other modes are Fast (With slight detail loss, suitable for browsing websites) and Ultrafast (With heavy detail loss, suitable for playing videos). " created="Fri, 19 Jan 2024 22:11:37 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I found that while using Neo Reader and annotating the My Daily Organizer PDF that palm rejection was not working as well so the screen was jumping around and some writing was not recognized, so I switched back to Balanced. It is interesting that none of the refresh modes have any description in relationship to writing. " created="Fri, 19 Jan 2024 22:15:18 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Updated &lt;a href=&quot;http://pagepark.frankmcpherson.net/archive.opml&quot;&gt;the monthly index to this site&lt;/a&gt;. Starting the third full year of writing my day notes here." created="Fri, 19 Jan 2024 14:23:08 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 18" created="Thu, 18 Jan 2024 21:19:19 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="18">
				<outline text="My latest purchase is the Boox Note Air 3C, which is a Android tablet that has a color eInk screen. If you are familiar with the Amazon Kindles but not familiar with eInk screens, they are the type of screen in the Kindles. Unlike traditional Kindles, the Note Air 3C supports writing and reading. If you have heard of the &lt;a href=&quot;https://remarkable.com/store/remarkable-2&quot;&gt;Remarkable tablets&lt;/a&gt;, the Note Air 3C is a competing product with which writing is as near to paper and pencil/pen as possible. Having now used the Note Air 3C for some time, I can recommend unequivocally the type of screen that comes with the Note Air, Remarkable, &lt;a href=&quot;https://supernote.com/pages/supernote-nomad?gad_source=1&quot;&gt;Supernote&lt;/a&gt;, or &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.amazon.com/Kindle-Scribe-the-first-Kindle-for-reading-writing-journaling-and-sketching/dp/B09BS26B8B&quot;&gt;Kindle Scribe&lt;/a&gt; rather than using the Apple Pencil on an iPad. " created="Thu, 18 Jan 2024 21:19:20 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="What separates the Boox Note Air 3C from competing products is that it has the Google Play store and is capable of running any Android application. Note however that eInk displays do not have the fast refresh of tradition tablet displays and therefore not all applications will run well,  but apps like Readwise Reader and Google Calendar are a  good fit. I narrowed my choices of which eInk device to buy to the &lt;a href=&quot;https://supernote.com/pages/supernote-nomad&quot;&gt;Supernote Nomad&lt;/a&gt; and the Boox Note Air 3C and then picked the Note Air 3C because it can run any Android app whereas the Supernote is limited to only the Kindle app. The tradeoff is that reviews indicate Supernote has some functionality in its note taking capability that Boox does not have, and the Supernote Nomad is smaller and lighter than the Note Air 3C." created="Thu, 18 Jan 2024 21:25:35 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 16" created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:26:27 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="16">
				<outline text="I really wish that people who published to the web thought more about their readers and less about their own self interests. To many sites are flat out hostile to readers. For example, I subscribe to Ars Technica's RSS feed, so I see their latest articles in my feed and I can right click to save that link to read later in Readwise Reader, except that I only get half the article because Ars tends to break up their articles across multiple pages. It feels like Ars does this intentionally to foruce me to go to their web site. What it does is cause to avoid reading their stuff. " created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 19:33:30 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://blogarchive.org/&quot;&gt;Blog Archive&lt;/a&gt; (.bar) is a file format for packaging up your blog posts and photos in a single file that can be moved between platforms. " created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 18:53:04 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Changing Organizational Culture" created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:49:12 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I see a lot of &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.mlive.com/lions/2024/01/yes-dan-campbell-kept-receipts-on-the-haters-of-detroits-rebuild.html&quot;&gt;articles&lt;/a&gt; about the turnaround of the Detroit Lions, but I don't think any of them get to the true reason. Dan Campbell and his coaching staff are pretty much all former NFL players, and I think that really matters to change the culture of an NFL team. First off the culture is about the players, and so it is formed by leaders who can relate to the players, most who have good B.S. detectors. The best example of this is the rate at which Campbell decides to keep the offense out on fourth down rather than punt.  " created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:26:28 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="I don't know if this is a fact, but I think it is true that historically the higher percentage of teams who &quot; go for it&quot; on fourth down is coached by former players, for example &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/news/ron-rivera-riverboat-ron-nickname-commanders-coach/1a57d21b60ca163e11f8348e&quot;&gt;Ron Rivera&lt;/a&gt;. Not much written about why this is the case, but I bet if you polled offensive players a majority would rather &quot;go for it&quot; than punt on fourth and short because they would rather control their own fate than give up the ball to the opponent. By their nature football players are aggressive. " created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:31:24 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Some coaches will talk about being aggressive, but in the game are anything but, and that is not Dan Campbell, and that earns him the respect of his players. Lions fans use the phrase &quot;Same Old Lions (SOL)&quot; that describes a history in which one way or another something, a mistake, a penalty, or bad call by a ref, will prevent the Lions from winning. How do you overcome SOL? By not waiting for something bad to happen!" created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:34:15 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="After the Lions lost to the Cowboys due in part to Campbell deciding to go for a 2 point conversion after a touchdown to take a 1 point lead with a minute or less to go in the game, many were critical of Campbell's decision. Here is the thing, that moment in that game was not just about winning the game, it was another step in dispelling SOL once and for all! Campbell is not afraid to make that decision that could and did not work because in making the decision he is achieving his bigger goal of changing the culture and turning the Lions in to a winning franchise. Clearest evidence of this is Campbell's post game comments stating in effect that he told his players, presumably before the game, that if that situation where to happen they were going for the win. Even when the Lions were backed up seven yards he still went for it, because he had to for the bigger picture." created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:37:27 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="And now, Campbell appears to be vindicated. Not only did the Lions win their first playoff game in 32 years, but they are now the second seed in the NFC and host another playoff game at home, which would have been the result if they had won that game in Dallas. In fact, an argument can be made everything worked out in the best manner for the Lions because the Packers had the best chance of beating Dallas in Dallas. " created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:41:44 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Enjoy the ride Lions fans, you deserve it. You are fortunate that your team finally has the leadership, void of the prima donnas of the past, not only capable of providing one hit wonders but a franchise that wins more than loses because they are committed to &lt;a href=&quot;https://simonsinek.com/books/the-infinite-game/&quot;&gt;the infinite game&lt;/a&gt;. Now is the time to not get too high nor too low, and have faith in that the Campbell and Holmes know what they are doing. " created="Tue, 16 Jan 2024 15:45:55 GMT" type="outline"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 12" created="Fri, 12 Jan 2024 16:00:54 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="12">
				<outline text="I've been thinking a lot about how the 14th amendment disqualifies Trump from being President, and I admit to having two minds about the topic. My thinking has evolved now to this: if the 2024 election is ONLY about Trump then it is right to disqualify him, HOWEVER, the election really is not about him, it's about 74,222,960 people (46.8% of those who voted) in the United States who voted for Trump, and because of them he ought to remain on the ballot. " created="Fri, 12 Jan 2024 15:50:05 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I do think it's right for one of the states, like Colorado, to call the question and have SCOTUS make a decision as the question is legit, and if the question isn't considered by the right parties those who do not vote for Trump could make a claim about his legitimacy. I personally think 14th amendment does apply, but what I am curious about is, does it apply to a primary or general election? My thinking is really it only applies to the general election but even then it might only apply to the electoral college election and Congress. In otherwords, won't it apply to the final decision makers, and that is either the general or electoral college elections. Now, a sane political party ought to want to know whether the candidate's they have running are qualified to hold the office and wouldn't want to put disqualified persons in their primary, but for most point of views sanity is not a factor of political parties." created="Fri, 12 Jan 2024 15:54:23 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 11" created="Thu, 11 Jan 2024 13:41:22 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="11">
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://bgr.com/tech/rabbit-r1-ai-gadget-is-now-sold-out-but-you-can-still-preorder-one/&quot;&gt;BGR reports&lt;/a&gt; that Rabbit Inc. received 10,000 orders for the R1, &lt;a href=&quot;http://oldschool.scripting.com/frank.mcpherson@gmail.com/2024/01/10/150158.html&quot;&gt;which I made note about yesterday&lt;/a&gt;, on the day they announced it. I imagine for many the $199 is throw away money. At least the price is low enough that if the company quickly goes away one will not have lost a thousand dollars. " created="Thu, 11 Jan 2024 19:33:52 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Learned that WiFi 7 is a thing. Might need to think about whether this is a time to upgrade the home network, I don't believe we are running WiFi 6." created="Thu, 11 Jan 2024 17:00:01 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Woke up way to early this morning and could not fall back asleep, therefore I will be running on lots of coffee." created="Thu, 11 Jan 2024 13:41:23 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 10" created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 13:59:42 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="10">
				<outline text="I've cleaned up my microBlog outline in Drummer by archiving the posts that I wrote in 2021 and 2022 to a separate OPML file." created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 13:59:43 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="Falling Down The Rabbit Hole" created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 15:01:58 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="Learned about &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.rabbit.tech/&quot;&gt;the rabbit r1&lt;/a&gt;, which is a new mobile device built on a Large Language Model. The underlying operating system, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.rabbit.tech/rabbit-os&quot;&gt;rabbit OS&lt;/a&gt;, does not run apps nor store files, its user interface is primarily natural language processing, and the device has a small touch screen to display information, including the text of verbal responses from the device. Conversation with rabbit is initiated by &quot;push to talk&quot; so it is not constantly listening. " created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 14:50:56 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.rabbit.tech/rabbit-os&quot;&gt;Rabbit OS&lt;/a&gt; includes what the company calls a Large Action Model that knows about the APIs of applications like Spotify and Uber, which the operating system uses to execute actions. One asks Rabbit to play music and LAM uses the Spotify API to identify and play the music that fulfills the request. The demo shows how one can interact to play another song from the same album as the song currently playing or ask who has covered the song. Also demoed were requests for a ride, fulfilled via Uber, and order a pizza, fulfilled via Door Dash. Finally, the demo shows how one will be able to teach Rabbit how to execute certain actions that you want it to perform for you like generating an animation using Stable Diffusion." created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 14:57:41 GMT"/>
					<outline text="What this company is doing here is using LLMs to enhance natural language processing so that it hears the speaker correctly, confirms what it heard, and then can perform specific actions. During the demo the person interacting with the device had an accent and did not appear to speak in any specific way and the device appeared to understand everything flawlessly. If this software and device works as reliably as demoed it addresses a frustration with all of the assistants from Google, Microsoft, Apple, and Amazon have in that none of these devices understand what is being spoken to it reliably.  " created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 15:01:14 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The Rabbit R1 will have 4G LTE, WiFi, and Bluetooth connectivity and all AI processing is said to be on the device. One uses a portal to configure the interfaces with the particular applications one wants to use. It's not clear whether one can make phone calls using the device, and the presenter of the demo stated the device is not intended to replace a smartphone. I wonder what certifications has been obtained for the device, and securing them could impact the spring ship date." created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 15:22:27 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The device is priced at $199 and there is no subscription model, which causes me to wonder how it is going to make money. The company has raised $30 million in total funding via &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.rabbit.tech/updates/rabbit-raises-20m&quot;&gt;two&lt;/a&gt; offerings. The company behind the device has nine people and is based in Los Angeles. Per the update from &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.rabbit.tech/updates/rabbit-raises-additional-10m&quot;&gt;the second offering&lt;/a&gt;:" created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 15:09:01 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&gt; Headquartered in Los Angeles, rabbit was founded by a group of top-ranking Kaggle Grandmasters, ex-Google engineers and repeat-entrepreneurs with extensive experience in creating AI hardware and operating high-performance computing clusters. A two-time Y Combinator alumnus, rabbit's Founder and CEO, Jesse Lyu, previously founded Raven Tech, a startup that pioneered conversational AI operatingsystems and was acquired by Baidu." created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 15:13:18 GMT" type="markdown"/>
					<outline text="I don't know whether the device is going to sell, but I think the software is interesting and worth keeping an eye on to see how well it is received. If successful, the most likely outcome is for the company/software to be acquired to be used in a larger scale. The web site says that you can pre-order the device that will ship on Easter, 2024. " created="Wed, 10 Jan 2024 15:14:16 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 9" created="Tue, 09 Jan 2024 21:30:27 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="09">
				<outline text="A lot of attention is being spent on Artificial Intelligence, with most seeing it as the next big technological iteration after mobile Internet access (smartphones), and that might be right. Consequently many are overlooking what the company responsible for that last iteration is &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.imore.com/vision-pro/apple-vision-pro-review&quot;&gt;launching this year&lt;/a&gt;, with Apple's Vision Pro going on sale in stores for $3,499. Much focus is on the hardware, but what one will be able to buy in February is analogous to &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.fastcompany.com/40436054/10-of-the-most-interesting-reactions-to-the-first-iphone-back-in-2007&quot;&gt;the original iPhone&lt;/a&gt;. Steve Jobs knew &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x7qPAY9JqE4&quot;&gt;when he announced that first iPhone&lt;/a&gt; that mobile Internet access will change the world, and it has for both good and ill. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/what-is-spatial-computing-a-basic-explainer&quot;&gt;Spatial Computing&lt;/a&gt; has the potential for changing how we interact with and thus use personal computing, while Artificial Intelligence has the potential for changing what personal computing does for and to us. " created="Tue, 09 Jan 2024 21:15:28 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 8" created="Mon, 08 Jan 2024 14:40:48 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="08">
				<outline text="I've started to use &lt;a href=&quot;https://support.goodnotes.com/hc/en-us/categories/7104265371023-Goodnotes-6&quot;&gt;GoodNotes&lt;/a&gt; more on my iPads, particularly using a planner template. I am storing the notebooks in iCloud that &lt;a href=&quot;https://support.goodnotes.com/hc/en-us/articles/7353726793999-Sync-Goodnotes-documents-between-iPhones-iPads-Macs&quot;&gt;syncs&lt;/a&gt; between my iPad Air and iPad Mini. I don't know for sure, but it looks like a notebook does not sync while it is open. I had my planner open on the iPad Mini and observed that the version on the Air was not current and didn't sync until it was closed on the Mini." created="Mon, 08 Jan 2024 14:40:49 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 4" created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 13:51:11 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="04">
				<outline text="Testing of the new Raspberry Pi 5 continues. &lt;a href=&quot;http://oldschool.scripting.com/frank.mcpherson@gmail.com/2024/01/03/165707.html#a183607&quot;&gt;As I noted yesterday&lt;/a&gt;, my plan is to use an NVMe SSD attached via PCie to the Pi as the primary storage, but the Pineberry Bottom Pi HAT I plan to use is out of stock. I decided to go ahead and buy &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.amazon.com/dp/B089DNM8LR?ref=ppx_yo2ov_dt_b_product_details&amp;th=1&quot;&gt;a NVMe drive&lt;/a&gt; and an &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08G14NBCS?psc=1&amp;ref=ppx_yo2ov_dt_b_product_details&quot;&gt;external NVMe SSD enclosure&lt;/a&gt; that will connect via USB 3 as I use that configure for my current &lt;a href=&quot;https://pi-hosted.com/&quot;&gt;pi-hosted&lt;/a&gt; server that uses a Rasbperry Pi 4. " created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 13:51:12 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I immediately had problems because it appeared the Raspberry Pi 5 would not boot from the USB-attached SSD. In hindsight I think the real issue was with the display, but in the process I changed the boot order to make NVMe/USB primary. While I then saw the Pi boot I then encountered another problem, the WiFi network connection mysteriously disappears.  I searched for information about whether others have had such a problem and found &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/raspberrypi/firmware/issues/1837&quot;&gt;a Github issue report&lt;/a&gt; via the Raspberry Pi forum that describes it almost exactly, and the recommended workaround is to revert to SD primary boot and USB secondary and that does seem to resolve the WiFi issue." created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 13:55:50 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="However, &lt;a href=&quot;https://forums.raspberrypi.com/viewtopic.php?p=2176147&amp;hilit=Raspberry+Pi+5#p2176147&quot;&gt;another issue&lt;/a&gt; appears to be related to how power is supplied to USB devices that another thread on the Raspberry Pi forum describes using the same drive enclosure that I am using. I am using the official, 5V5A, 27 Watt Raspberry Pi power supply so that should be supplying enough power. I am going to fiddle some with this, I would like to at least run a storage benchmark to see how much faster the NVMe drive persforms, but I also have a SATA SSD in a USB enclosure that I could use for the time being. " created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 13:59:44 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="More SSD Testing with RPI 5" created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 16:33:03 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="I am using the &lt;a href=&quot;https://pibenchmarks.com/&quot;&gt;pibenchmarks.com&lt;/a&gt; storage test and find that it consistently crashes the Raspberry Pi 5 when I have the Orico enclosure with Crucial SSD connected to a USB 3 port. The script installs some utilities that it then runs and it fails to install and commands already on the device like cat are indicated as not being available. I can't close any desktop window and when I attempt to shutdown the device I end up seeing a blank screen, and I can no longer SSH in to the device or does it respond to pings." created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 16:33:36 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I plugged the enclosure into the USB 2 port and it executes successfully, but as expected I observe that the &lt;a href=&quot;https://pibenchmarks.com/benchmark/76951/&quot;&gt;performance due to USB 2&lt;/a&gt; is half that of &lt;a href=&quot;https://pibenchmarks.com/benchmark/76920/&quot;&gt;the SD card&lt;/a&gt;  so no way one would want to use an SSD like this on USB 2. Next, I am going to flash my SATA SSD with Raspberry Pi OS and see how stable it is on USB 3. " created="Thu, 04 Jan 2024 16:38:41 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 3" created="Wed, 03 Jan 2024 16:52:05 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="03">
				<outline text="Raspberry Pi 5 Testing" created="Wed, 03 Jan 2024 16:57:07 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="Yesterday I got the Raspberry Pi 5 assembled and did some preliminary testing. Today I am doing more in-depth testing, first using the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.tomshardware.com/how-to/raspberry-pi-benchmark-vcgencmd&quot;&gt;Tom's Hardware test&lt;/a&gt; to see how the thermals looks using the Active Cooler and the official Pi 5 case. The highest temperature was 74.7 degrees Celsius with the top of the case on, I am letting the Pi 5 cool down over lunch and then I am going to run the test again with the top off. While that temperature is pretty high, it did not result in CPU throttling. I ran this test another time from a cold start and the highest temperature was 65.9 degrees. " created="Wed, 03 Jan 2024 16:52:06 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="I ran the test a second time after a cool down and the top of the case removed so that the entry top of the board, fan, and heatsink are all directly exposed. The highest temperature in this run was 60.4 degrees, a pretty significant decrease. I think this tells me that if I am to run this board under heavy load I should either keep the top of the case off or put the board and active cooler in a different case." created="Wed, 03 Jan 2024 18:23:49 GMT" type="outline"/>
					<outline text="Next, I ran the &lt;a href=&quot;https://pibenchmarks.com/benchmark/76920/&quot;&gt;pibenchmarks.com storage benchmark test on the SandDisk Ultra 128 GB SD Card&lt;/a&gt; that is currently in use and it got a score of 1770; Disk Read of 78.32 MB/sec; Cached Disk Red of 55.55 MB/sec; Disk Write of 63.9 MB/sec. FIO 4k random read of 3348 IOS (13392 KB/s) and FIO 4k random write of 729 IOS (2916 KB/s). I will compare these against a Kingston NVMe SSD attached via USB 3 that is in route. I plan to get a &lt;a href=&quot;https://pineberrypi.com/products/hatdrive-bottom-2230-2242-2280-for-rpi5&quot;&gt;Pinberry Pi HAT&lt;/a&gt; to attach the NVMe drive via the PCIe connectory on the Raspbery Pi 5. " created="Wed, 03 Jan 2024 18:36:07 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="January 2" created="Tue, 02 Jan 2024 14:11:32 GMT" type="calendarDay" name="02">
				<outline text="I use &lt;a href=&quot;https://restic.net/&quot;&gt;restic&lt;/a&gt; to backup files from a file server to a S3 bucket. Today &lt;a href=&quot;https://blog.fidelramos.net/software/homelab&quot;&gt;I learned&lt;/a&gt; about a similar product called &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.borgbackup.org/&quot;&gt;BorgBackup&lt;/a&gt;. " created="Tue, 02 Jan 2024 22:05:10 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="The power supply for the Raspberry Pi 5 should be arriving in the mail today, then I will be able to assemble it." created="Tue, 02 Jan 2024 14:28:00 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="I completed the primary project I planned for the holiday break, building a PiKVM and connecting it to the Beelink U59 Pro that is hosting one of my Proxmox nodes. Once I got past the stupid issue of plugging the FFC cable in to the wrong port, it was a breeze to set up. I put the Raspberry Pi back in to the MazerPi case, and it all works the only issue is the that the fan in the MazerPi case is noisy. Noisy enough for me to hear it as soon as I walk in to the room where it is running. " created="Tue, 02 Jan 2024 14:22:30 GMT" type="outline"/>
				<outline text="It's a new year!" created="Tue, 02 Jan 2024 14:11:31 GMT" type="outline"/>
				</outline>
			</outline>
